भाग ७ : ऐन्दवोपाख्यान का प्रारम्भ
Brahma Gītā – Aindava Upākhyāna (Sarga 178)
Part Seven: The Beginning of the Sacred Story
मूल श्लोक
कस्मिंश्चित्प्राक्तनेनैव जगज्जालेऽभवद्विजः।
तपोवेदक्रियाधारो ब्राह्मण इन्दुरिति स्मृतः॥२८॥
दश तस्याभवन् पुत्रा जगतो दिक्तटा इव।
महाशया महात्मानो महतामास्पदं सताम्॥२९॥
स तेषां कालवशतः पितान्तर्धिमुपाययौ।
दशानां भगवान् रुद्र एकादश इव क्षये॥३०॥
तस्यानुगमनं चक्रे भार्या वैधव्यभीतिभिः।
अनुरक्ता दिनस्येव संध्या ताराविलोचना॥३१॥

🌿 हिन्दी भावार्थ
अब श्रीवसिष्ठजी तर्क से कथा की ओर प्रवेश करते हैं।
वे कहते हैं—
किसी प्राचीन काल में एक अत्यन्त महान ब्राह्मण थे, जिनका नाम इन्दु था।
वे केवल जन्म से ब्राह्मण नहीं थे।
वे तप, वेद-अध्ययन और वैदिक आचरण के आधार-स्तम्भ थे।
उनके दस पुत्र थे।
वे साधारण पुत्र नहीं थे।
वे दसों दिशाओं के समान विशाल हृदय वाले,
महात्मा,
सज्जनों के आश्रय,
और उच्च चरित्र से सम्पन्न थे।
समय का नियम सब पर समान रूप से लागू होता है।
एक दिन ब्राह्मण इन्दु भी शरीर त्यागकर अन्तर्धान हो गये।
उनकी धर्मपत्नी, जो उनसे अत्यन्त अनुरक्त थीं,
पति-वियोग सहन न कर सकीं
और उसी प्रकार उनका अनुसरण कर गयीं,
जैसे सन्ध्या अस्त होते सूर्य का अनुसरण करती है।
इस प्रकार कथा की भूमिका पूर्ण होती है।
किन्तु वेदान्त में कोई कथा केवल कथा नहीं होती।
प्रत्येक पात्र,
प्रत्येक घटना,
और प्रत्येक परिस्थिति
आत्मविद्या का एक सूक्ष्म संकेत है।

🌿 English Reflection
Having established the non-dual vision through philosophical inquiry,
Sage Vasiṣṭha now begins teaching through a sacred narrative.
In an ancient world there lived a noble Brāhmaṇa named Indu.
He was renowned not merely for learning,
but for a life rooted in austerity,
Vedic wisdom,
and righteous conduct.
He had ten sons,
each noble in character,
vast in understanding,
and compared to the ten directions,
suggesting universality rather than limitation.
In time,
as happens to every embodied being,
Indu departed from the visible world.
His devoted wife,
unable to bear separation,
followed him,
just as the evening twilight lovingly follows the setting sun.
At first glance,
this appears to be a simple family history.
Yet the Yoga Vāsiṣṭha never tells stories merely to entertain.
Every character is symbolic.
Every event carries philosophical significance.
The narrative has only begun.
Its deeper meaning will gradually unfold.

🌿 Vedantic Insight
One of the greatest teaching methods of Maharshi Vasiṣṭha is this:
He first establishes Truth through reason.
Then he allows that Truth to blossom through story.
A philosophical principle may satisfy the intellect.
A sacred narrative allows the same truth to become living experience.
Thus, the Aindava Upākhyāna is not separate from Advaita.
It is Advaita expressed in the language of life.

🌿 Practical Contemplation
Every person who enters our life,
every relationship,
every meeting,
and every departure
becomes meaningful when viewed through the eye of wisdom.
Vedānta teaches us to look beyond events
and inquire into the Reality that illumines every event.
When we learn to see life in this way,
ordinary history becomes sacred teaching.

🌸 Living Vedanta Library Conclusion
The story has begun.
Yet its true subject is not a Brāhmaṇa,
nor his sons,
nor even their earthly lives.
Its true subject is Consciousness itself.
Maharshi Vasiṣṭha gently invites us to enter the story,
until we discover
that we are not merely reading about Indu—
we are reading about the journey of our own mind,
our own identity,
and our own awakening.
For every sacred story ultimately points back to the one eternal Truth:
The Self alone is Real.
Everything else is its passing appearance.
